{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538022"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:23:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:23:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16118"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16118"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.14,0.17,0.15,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103250"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8809"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16118"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85668"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"5808"},{"type":"tags","id":"5809"},{"type":"tags","id":"9051"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48619"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103250"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with worsening chronic pain affecting multiple joints. She has a confirmed diagnosis of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome (hypermobility type). She reports recurrent joint dislocations, particularly affecting her shoulders and fingers, easy bruising, and chronic fatigue. Her pain significantly impacts her daily activities and sleep.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a medical history of depression, gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, and iron deficiency anaemia. Her current medications include escitalopram, pantoprazole, and oral iron supplements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She demonstrates skin hyperextensibility, bilateral thumb opposition to the forearm, and bilateral elbow and knee hyperextension beyond 10 degrees. Multiple tender points are noted around her major joints.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following interventions has shown the least benefit in managing her pain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Codeine","Graded exercise program","Cognitive behavioural therapy","Non-steroidal anti-inflammatories","Duloxetine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has hypermobility-type Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, a condition characterised by chronic pain, joint instability, and soft tissue fragility. Management of chronic noncancer pain is complex and should be multidisciplinary, focusing on improving function and quality of life while minimising harm. Nonpharmacological management incorporating multiple modalities, including psychotherapy and physical exercise, is first-line. Analgesics are second-line management, which should be used in conjunction with first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECodeine\u003C/strong\u003E and other opioid medications have not demonstrated sustained benefit in chronic noncancer pain management. There is a significant risk of dependence, tolerance, and adverse effects, and guidelines recommend avoiding opioids for chronic non-cancer pain, especially in younger people. Evidence supports non-pharmacological and selected non-opioid pharmacological approaches instead.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraded exercise programs\u003C/strong\u003E are a mainstay of management, with evidence supporting their role in improving muscle strength, joint stability, and overall function. Exercise regimens should be individualised and supervised to avoid injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECognitive behavioural therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is effective in helping people develop coping strategies for chronic noncancer pain and addressing associated psychological symptoms, such as depression and anxiety, which are common in Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-steroidal anti-inflammatories\u003C/strong\u003E may provide short-term relief for musculoskeletal pain, although their use should be cautious due to potential gastrointestinal and renal side effects, especially in people with comorbidities. They are not a long-term solution but can be part of a multimodal approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuloxetine\u003C/strong\u003E is a serotonin-noradrenaline reuptake inhibitor (SNRI) with demonstrated efficacy in treating chronic neuropathic pain, major depression, and generalised anxiety disorder. It is a helpful adjuvant therapy when these are present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic noncancer pain management requires a comprehensive approach and multimodal management.","First-line management consists of multimodal nonpharmacological approaches, such as physical exercise and psychotherapy.","Analgesics are second-line management, which should be used along with first-line management.","Opioid medications, including codeine, have limited evidence of benefit and significant risk in chronic noncancer pain management.","Adjuvant therapy may be beneficial in selected patients (e.g., neuropathic pain, comorbid depression or anxiety)."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Pain and Analgesia. In: Therapeutic Guidelines [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2023 [cited 2025 May 17]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85668"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16118"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85668"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T21:28:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-20T21:28:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8809"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103250"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null